    value: 천산(天山) 남쪽의 사막(沙漠).
english:
  title: Climbing Mirror Lake Pavilion
  author: Sung Hyun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Great Ridge towers into empty space like ancient fathers,
    With wrinkled ridges streaming eastward, scattering like limbs.
    Where arms divide and legs spread wide, they embrace the level lake,
    As green peaks and white waves swallow and disgorge each other.

    Ten miles of tranquil water spreads before me—
    A mirror polished, reflecting like a lotus dressing case.
    Seagulls arrive to kick the crystalline surface,
    Their jade feathers trembling in spring wind, rippling soft.

    Bamboo groves in verdant green blanket the island,
    While setting sun gilds the red bridge, casting inverted shadows.
    A serpentine path winds toward the seaside,
    Where wild crabapple blooms scatter their crimson light on emerald grass.

    Distant whale-waves stretch to meet the great ocean,
    And cloud-sails journey ten thousand leagues toward Fusang.
    Yet Fusang cannot be reached, though searched for far—
    Only Dragon Heaps and mirage halls shimmer distantly.

    What beauty could match these wonders and vistas?
    Within all the world, surely these rank first.
    Dongting and Yunmeng lakes merely borrow their fame;
    Qi's boasting and Chu's claims are hard to trust.

    The immortals have long departed, clouds drift alone,
    Clear wind and bright moon empty the autumn river.
    How many poets and artists have come and gone!
    Each year they bring wine for spring's wandering pleasures.

    I arrive as late spring fades to its end,
    Mountain blossoms falling thick, scattering crimson rain.
    Reciting ancient verses, I whistle long and clear,
    As gentle wind arrives to stir the green trees.
  footnotes:
    - 'Fusang (扶桑): In Chinese mythology, a legendary tree marking the eastern limit of the world, representing the far reaches of the known universe.'
    - 'Dragon Heaps (龍堆): Desert regions south of the Heavenly Mountains, symbolizing distant and inaccessible lands.'
    - 'Dongting and Yunmeng: Famous lakes in southern China, referenced here as lesser in beauty than Mirror Lake.'
